caption: Sukiyaki way too sweet, chawanmushi is underwhelming, miso soup too salty.  Tofu is good, does taste like noodle Appetizers are all pretty good. My experience at Yoshitsune with my fiancé was so wonderful and authentic. We both ordered dinner course B, which had good portion sizes, was brought out in thoughtful courses and presented so nicely. The butterfish was especially melt-in-your-mouth delicious!  It was a perfect blend of upper scale dining and nostalgia from my childhood trips to visit family in Japan. Service was prompt and gracious as well. ごちそうさまでした。
I almost don't want this place discovered.  Great food at very reasonable prices for the quality and expertise. Great experience everytime so far.

I don’t recommend this place. We chose this place for dinner among tons of Japanese restaurants based on lots of compliment and good comments online. Even though the host grandma is friendly, the food quality and service is not that good. Firstly, the sukiyaki with prime beef is not that good for $68 value, the beef quality is tough and not juicy at all compared to others. For me, all San Diego restaurants can beat this place. Secondly, there was smoke all over the place, might be due to the sukiyaki smoke. Also, there was a fly flying over the appetizer and we need to request to be changed. Finally, we waited more than 40 minutes just for the check. Yes 40 mins! During the waiting we are trying to be nice and another younger hostess checked 3-4 times to see if we got the check. However, we don’t have the check even the other tables called the check after us. The overall dining time is more than 2.5 hrs incredibly. The only good thing is the grandma hostess was nice and gave us 1 more egg for Sukiyaki for free. However, you may would like to go to other places with better food and lower price definitely based on my comment. I really don’t recommend this place to any of my friend.

Having lived in Japan for 8 years, Yoshitsune hit the spot.  Called as soon as they opened to make reservations for 6 (2 at one table and 4 at the other due to COVID).  The tempura is on point, the Sukiyaki was straight out of Tokyo and the Asahi beer?  COLD.  Kids had the Udon, chicken teriyaki and sashimi that was incredible and I highly recommend this place for some authentic Japanese eats.  The bill for 6 was $369, but I did have 5 large beers with short glasses...just like in Japan.  Oh and one last thing, if you don't get an egg with your Sukiyaki then it ain't the real deal.  We got the egg.

COVID-RISKY! Don't go here if you are a germaphobe or strict-masker.  Pros: *Grandma server was friendly and nice. *Their signature homemade tofu appetizer was YUMMY. *Big extensive menu, food was quick & it had an authentic Japanese vibe.  Cons: *There were 2 sushi chefs and one of them (not the guy preparing our food) was NOT wearing his mask (he had it under his chin for 90% of the time we were there!) He was yelling goodbyes and responses to orders consistently over the food with no mask on which made us very nervous. He was constantly touching the counter, the order papers, and at one point he wiped his nose with one finger. I understand sushi chefs may not wear gloves because of sushi rolling but then they shouldn't touch so many things especially their face during a pandemic! *Hawaii state law for indoor dining is 50% capacity but the room we were in was at 100% capacity. It was clear there were 2 other rooms judging by where customers were being taken by the servers so not sure how full they were but our room was full and the tables were barely 5 feet apart. (Diners were definitely closer than 5 feet apart.) *The room was quite warm and I wonder about the ventilation.  If it wasn't for the restaurant not following covid regulations, we would definitely go back there!

caption: This restaurant is a nice respite from the growing plethora of Japanese fusion restaurants, serving up closer to the traditional sushi shop where the appreciation and craftsmanship is focused on the fish, rice, and the interplay of flavours. They also have a pretty good selection of sake to accompany the meal.  I stopped in one night for their omakase for dinner. Well worth the price, serving up 16 distinct pieces of nigirizushi all well-crafted. The cuts of fish were fresh, and most pieces had a good balance of wasabi and other flavours. They presented the raw shrimp first then asked if I wanted the head deep-fried -- an unexpected but nice departure from sushi restaurants in the West that go straight to deep-frying.  Their housemade tofu was very delicate, smooth, and light - delicious!  Service was also very attentive, and catered towards the American audience (e.g. I was immediately offered cold water instead of some hot tea).  Only things I found disappointing were seating me at a full table when a bar seat would've been nice, and the dessert that came with dinner. When ordering an omakase set, part of the experience is chats with the chef and receiving a brief explanation of each piece; unfortunately the servers just dropped off each plate and walked away, without even mentioning the fish (if you're a sushi fanatic you'll recognize the cuts, but less helpful to novice diners). They also only offer typical ice cream flavours (like vanilla, green tea, red bean); authentic Japanese desserts would have been nice.

This restaurant is located in a hotel, a little bit hard to find.  The food were nice. True Japanese style, and really fishy, like, fishy-fishy. If you don’t like fishy food then don’t order any seafood expect shrimp.  The environment was moderate, servers cannot clean up in time, and noise level was high.  They provided course menu, which is a “fine-dinning”standard thing, but price was reasonable.
Absolutely delicious

The first visit, I would have given a five star. For a good food and finding a good seat even without reserving it.  However when we visited there the second time we just didn’t get any service what so over. We reserved the seat over the phone and once we arrived there a bit early we still didn’t get seated for a good 30 min. Once we got the seat, we still waited for again 30-40 min to get menu!  We truly felt like we were treated poorly. We had to ask for the menu to be given to us, and the waitress just threw it at us.  We are sorry if we can’t speak Japanese, but I don’t think it is the reason to treat us any different then anyone else in the place. We weren’t disrespectful, we waited as long as we could.  Overall we reserved the seat for 6:30 and got seated at 7. We got the menu at around 7:35-7:40. And we got food only at around 8:30. If the waitress or the staff had communicated with us more properly and respectfully, then it would have been a perfect evening. But with such a service the waiting time just felt too long.  Bottom line, do you want to feel like an outsider? Do you want to be looked down upon? Well if you can’t speak Japanese this is the place for you.  If you do; however, speak Japanese, then it will be an amazing place for you.

They're called Kaiseki dinners--multi-coursed and truly remarkable for it's purity of taste, simple, clean flavors.  I had an AMAZING Chirashi Kaiseki dinner. My friend and I came here twice on our 5 day trip, because the food was so good. My favorite thing is the tofu a ponzu sauce that as so delicate and clean in flavor. It was really, really nice!

Traditional Japanese (no fancy rolls). The service was pretty good. A bit pushy but i guess that's their style. They definitely give you a lot of food for your money. Unfortunately the fish portions are very small (i got the chirashi).  Overall good but probably wouldn't return.
